-- =============================================================================
-- S23. IMPLEMENTATION NOTES (key algorithms, caching, known bugs)
-- =============================================================================
--
-- Key Algorithm: Neuromorphic Intent Routing (cortex.rs)
--   1. Receive raw message via Zenoh subscriber
--   2. Deserialize into TaskIntent struct
--   3. Check for ACK (early return, no LLM)
--   4. Send immediate ack to chat channel
--   5. Construct RETE-UL rule input from stress level
--   6. Attempt LLM inference via mcp_inference
--   7. On LLM failure: fallback to stress-based priority
--   8. If text starts with '/' or len > 10: create task via db::add_task
--   9. Send cortex response to chat channel
--
-- Caching:
--   - Telegram offset cached in Smriti.db under "infra_state" category
--   - Channel credentials cached in Smriti.db preferences table
--   - No in-memory LRU cache for messages (stateless polling)
--
-- Known Limitations:
--   - WhatsApp support is compile-time gated (enable_whatsapp = false)
--   - GChat Pub/Sub requires gcloud CLI installed on host
--   - Simulator uses raw TCP (not axum/warp) for minimal dependency footprint
--   - Rate limiter is per-process (not persisted across restarts)
--   - LLM inference is single-model only (tinyllama); model routing not implemented

-- =============================================================================
-- S24. DESIGN PRINCIPLES & PATTERNS
-- =============================================================================
--
-- Principles:
--   1. Dark Cockpit Architecture: Egress-only polling (no inbound webhooks).
--      The daemon polls outward; never exposes a public endpoint.
--   2. Rule-First, LLM-Escalation: RETE-UL rules handle classification;
--      LLM is advisory and non-blocking.
--   3. Graceful Degradation: Every channel operates independently.
--      Telegram failure does not affect GChat and vice versa.
--   4. Offset Persistence: Telegram polling offset survives restarts.
--      No message replay, no message loss.
--   5. Simulator Parity: Test harness produces API-identical responses.
--      Tests run without real credentials.
--
-- Patterns:
--   - Spawn-on-Receive: Intent processing spawned as tokio tasks (non-blocking select)
--   - Publish-on-Transition: State changes published to Zenoh topics
--   - Fallback Chain: LLM -> Rule-based -> Static response
--   - Credential Resolution: Smriti DB -> Environment variable -> Default/mock
--   - Preflight Gate: GChat subscription verified before entering poll loop

-- =============================================================================
-- S25. ANTI-PATTERNS (things to AVOID)
-- =============================================================================
--
-- 1. Blocking the select loop: NEVER process intents inline in the select! branch.
--    Always tokio::spawn. Violation blocks ALL channels.
-- 2. Hardcoded credentials: NEVER embed API tokens in source code.
--    Always resolve from Smriti.db or env vars.
-- 3. Unbounded inbox: NEVER accumulate messages without processing.
--    The simulator uses VecDeque with pop_front for bounded consumption.
-- 4. Ignoring poll offset: NEVER restart polling from offset=0.
--    Causes full message replay and duplicate processing.
-- 5. Synchronous LLM calls in hot path: NEVER call LLM synchronously.
--    The 60s recalculate timer is separate from the intent select loop.
-- 6. Silent channel failure: NEVER swallow send_message errors.
--    Log error and update GatewayChannel.last_error.
-- 7. In-memory only state: NEVER store critical state (offset, tokens) only in memory.
--    Smriti.db is the authoritative persistence layer.

